category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to make a field that only accepts digits (for example, a ZIP-code field), i.e. make sure the user can't type any other characters into it.</p>
discussion=<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent whenever a character key is pressed. If the blinking text cursor is in a field, the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent to that field. When the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message is sent to the field, it triggers this handler.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The parameter, which we call &quot;theKey&quot; in this example, is the character that was pressed. For example, if you press the &quot;A&quot; key, the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message that is sent has &quot;A&quot; as its parameter. This means we can simply check whether the parameter is a number to find out whether to accept the keypress or not.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">is a</font> operator can accept strings that contain non-digits as numbers. For example, &quot;22.5&quot; is a number even though it contains a period. However, the parameter to the keyDown message is always a single character, and for a single character to be a number, it must be a digit from 0 to 9.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The Revolution engine must receive the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message in order to respond to a typed character (or in other words, the entry of a character is triggered by the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> message), so trapping the message and not passing it prevents typing from being entered in the field.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>If the character that was pressed isn't a number, the <font face="Courier" size="11">keyDown</font> handler beeps to alert the user to the mistake, and doesn't <font face="Courier" size="11">pass</font> the message on, preventing the character from appearing in the field. If the character is a number, the handler uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">pass</font> control structure to allow the keyDown message to proceed along the message path.  For more details on the message path, see the section <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>The Message Path</i></font> in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Accepting only digit characters during data entry
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> keyDown theKey</p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">if</font> theKey is not a <font color="#FF0000">number</font> <font color="#980517">then</font> <font color="#0000FF">beep</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#980517">else</font> <font color="#0000FF">pass</font> keyDown</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> keyDown</p>
title=Accepting only digit characters during data entry